{"id":"2305.18917","submitter":"Yuval Reif","authors":"Yuval Reif, Roy Schwartz","title":"Fighting Bias with Bias: Promoting Model Robustness by Amplifying\n  Dataset Biases","comments":"Findings of ACL 2023","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.CL","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  NLP models often rely on superficial cues known as dataset biases to achieve\nimpressive performance, and can fail on examples where these biases do not\nhold. Recent work sought to develop robust, unbiased models by filtering biased\nexamples from training sets. In this work, we argue that such filtering can\nobscure the true capabilities of models to overcome biases, which might never\nbe removed in full from the dataset. We suggest that in order to drive the\ndevelopment of models robust to subtle biases, dataset biases should be\namplified in the training set. We introduce an evaluation framework defined by\na bias-amplified training set and an anti-biased test set, both automatically\nextracted from existing datasets. Experiments across three notions of bias,\nfour datasets and two models show that our framework is substantially more\nchallenging for models than the original data splits, and even more challenging\nthan hand-crafted challenge sets. Our evaluation framework can use any existing\ndataset, even those considered obsolete, to test model robustness. We hope our\nwork will guide the development of robust models that do not rely on\nsuperficial biases and correlations. To this end, we publicly release our code\nand data.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 30 May 2023 10:10:42 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-05-31"}
{"id":"2305.18918","submitter":"Tim Kokkeler","authors":"Tim Kokkeler, Alexander Golubov, Sebasti\\'an Bergeret, Yukio Tanaka","title":"Proximity effect of time-reversal symmetry broken non-centrosymmetric\n  superconductors","comments":"13 pages, 18 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.supr-con","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  In non-centrosymmetric superconductors the pair potential has both\neven-parity singlet and odd-parity triplet components. If time-reversal\nsymmetry is broken, the superconducting phase of these components is not the\nsame, for example in anapole superconductors. In this paper it is shown that\nbreaking time-reversal symmetry by a phase difference between the two\ncomponents significantly alters both the density of states and the conductance\nin s+helical p-wave superconductors. The density of states and conductance in\ns+chiral p-wave superconductors are less influenced by adding a phase\ndifference because time reversal symmetry is already broken in the s+p-wave\nsuperconductor. The Tanaka-Nazarov boundary conditions are extended to 3D\nsuperconductors, allowing to investigate a greater variety of superconductors,\nsuch as B-W superconductors, in which the direction of the d-vector is parallel\nto the direction of momentum. The results are important for the determination\nof pair potentials in potentially time-reversal symmetry broken\nnon-centrosymmetric superconductors.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 30 May 2023 10:14:47 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-05-31"}
{"id":"2305.18919","submitter":"Francesca Pelusi Dr.","authors":"Francesca Pelusi, Fabio Guglietta, Marcello Sega, Othmane Aouane and\n  Jens Harting","title":"A sharp interface approach for wetting dynamics of hydrophobic coated\n  droplets and soft particles","comments":"13 pages, 6 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.flu-dyn physics.comp-ph","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  Wetting dynamics may significantly impact technological applications\ninvolving some liquids, from coated droplets to soft particles. Indeed, in some\ncases, external conditions can trigger alterations in the interface properties\nof simple droplets, leading to variations in the mechanical interface response,\neven resulting in the acquisition of rigidity. This work explores the wetting\ndynamics of hydrophobic coated droplets with generic interface properties by\ncombining the immersed boundary (IB) and the lattice Boltzmann (LB) methods.\nThe presented model allows to explore different situations, corresponding to\ndifferent levels of droplet interface stiffness. We first validate our\nmethodology with the theoretical predictions in the context of shear flow and\nwetting experiments. Then, we show the effectiveness of our numerical framework\nto access the hydrophobic wetting dynamics, also providing a theoretical\nprediction for contact angles. Model limits are also discussed. To generalise\nthe application of our methodology, we present a numerical framework to study a\nwide spectrum of coated droplets and soft particles with varying interfacial\nproperties. It can serve as an initial approximation to investigate the wetting\ndynamics of specific coated droplets, like liquid metal droplets, which are\nobserved to exhibit large contact angles on any solid surface and whose wetting\nproperties can be altered when entering into contact with oxygen because of\nforming a solid-like oxide layer on the top of the inter